What happened to F13 was not GUN's/Illfonic's fault, yet people seem to lump it in with them (GUN) abandoning TCM. They literally couldn't do anything with the F13 lawsuit, they couldn't even add a new tree or a rock to a map, a developer literally said this. Its understandable why they eventually gave up, they were just waiting around doing nothing while two guys argued over money and a settlement.  As for TCM I never bought it (so far), but them abandoning support for it so soon, I agree it is bad. However, Illfonic had nothing to do with TCM so I see more hope for this. Carpenter is also credited as an executive producer which is a major bonus.  Also, for those complaining that the singleplayer experience will either just be offline bots, something like the F13 challenges, or the virtual cabin, literally do your research morons. The Halloween Game website literally says it in black and white:  "IllFonic dives into why making a singleplayer narrative in Halloween was a must. The narrative for singleplayer in Halloween takes on a new shape. Playing as Michael Myers, walk through memorable locations from the 1978 classic such as the Myers House or bask in the recreated atmosphere of Haddonfield".  Lets just see how it plays out and actually give it a chance before prematurely calling it a failure. I'm a huge Halloween fan, I see Halloween and I'm there for it Day 1. If its anywhere near as fun as F13 was (which was waaaaay more fun than Dead By Daylight regardless of the bugs/glitches) this will be awesome.  If it happens a 2nd time (like with TCM) then yeah there's a pattern forming. Call me a sucker or whatever, but its Halloween, as a fan of the series I can't not be there for this. Especially since it has a singleplayer mode.

When I was a kid, I was told rainbow doesn't really exists, it is a result of the scattering of light by water droplets.  As a result everyone see a different rainbow since it is all in our brain.  But some curious kid asked why does it arch?  The teacher has no answer other than say that each of our cornea is bent slightly so when that scattered light goes into your lense, it gets bent again through refraction and so you see the arch.    The teacher than proceeded to show us how to see rainbow by looking a fringes of soap films.  I am sure many of you old enough probably still remember.  And you probably also remember seeing rainbow after a rain.   Well, I am sorry to report to you that I can no longer see the rainbow.  I am not sure if this applies to you.  About 20 years ago, I was in the hospital for a life threatening emergency.  It didn't hit me at the time but something changed in me.  I started hearing a constant ringing in my right ears, eventually it settled to just blowing air in and out.  It eventually went away after my child was born, but it came back after a few years and it's been a constant static background even as I am typing this.    A few years back when I ended up in a psyche ward, the people in there told me about hearing voices, eventually for a brief moment I herd voices too and then I heard some chiming as if I was picking up some TV signal of a game show.   Before all this I also experienced a brief moments of complete blindness which wrecked my vision for a while but when I got it back, I feel like I got a different set of eyes.  You see my eyes has these horizontal lines across one of them and the other is burst with small lines cracks.  This is because I had really high blood pressure in the past that caused the veins in my eyes to burst.  The one withe cat eye was the functioning one, the crack one is quite weak, this is why I needed prescription glasses to compensate for the difference.  But now both of my eyes are of equal strength but weaker than before but few damages from my days of high blood pressure.    I suspect I lost the ability to see rainbows originally because I really did damaged my cornea.  But I don't think my current cornea were mine, someone may have replaced them without my consent.  As for that ringing in the ear, I don't know.  All I know is I don't think the people I met in the psyche ward were all crazy.   I know at least my roommate was pretending because he said he doesn't want to be homeless on the street.

The most awful thing in the world is to have doubts and fears about where you will spend eternity.  The good news is that God has told us in the Bible how to have eternal life.  Eternal life is available to anyone and that includes you!  The way of salvation is outlined in the four following statements:  YOU MUST REALIZE that you are a sinner.  The Bible says that ‚Äúall have sinned and come short of the glory of God‚Äù (Romans 3:23).  To ‚Äúsin‚Äù means to break God‚Äôs law, to miss the mark, or step out of bounds.  We are all guilty!  Sin brings separation from God and the life that God offers.   YOU MUST RECOGNIZE that Jesus is God‚Äôs Son.  The most familiar verse in the Bible says, ‚ÄúFor God so loved the world, that he gave his only begotten Son, that whosoever believeth in him should not perish, but have everlasting life‚Äù (John 3:16).  Jesus died on the cross for your sin.  Jesus arose from the dead to purchase your salvation.   YOU MUST REPENT of your sin.  Jesus said, ‚ÄúExcept ye repent, ye shall all likewise perish‚Äù (Luke 13:3,5).  ‚ÄúRepent‚Äù means to have a change of mind that results in a change of heart and a change of direction.  It is like making a u-turn on the highway.  Repentance is saying, ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt like the road I‚Äôm on.  I don‚Äôt like the direction I‚Äôm headed.  I sure don‚Äôt like where this road is taking me.‚Äù  YOU MUST RECEIVE Jesus as your Savior.  The Bible says that, ‚Äúas many as received him, to them gave he power to become the sons of God, even to them that believe on his name‚Äù (John 1:12).  To ‚Äúreceive‚Äù Jesus means to place your faith in Him.  All you have to do is accept Jesus and confess Him as your personal Savior and Lord.  HERE IS A SUGGESTED PRAYER.  Please know that there is nothing magical about praying words that you do not mean.  But, if these words express what you would like to say to God, pray this prayer from the depths of your heart:  ‚ÄúDear Lord Jesus, thank you for loving me.  I believe that you are God‚Äôs Son.  I believe that you died  for my sin and rose again from dead.  I am ready to turn from sin and I am asking you to come into my life and take control of my life.  Please forgive me of my sin.  I give you all of my life for the rest of my life.  Thank you, Lord Jesus, for hearing my prayer and giving me eternal life.  Help me to live every day for you.  In Jesus name, Amen!‚Äù

We covered a number of notable engineering failures in our engineering ethics module at university: Challenger, the Therac-25, the loss of the first Ariane 5 flight (and the Mars Crashing Orbiter got talked about because we enjoyed having a good laugh at NASA's expense!).    This one should also be in the syllabus as an example of a good outcome from an engineer performing ethically.  Failure is a great teacher, sure, but there's something to also be said for learning from other people's successes.  He owned up to his mistake and the work was done to fix it.  And the consequences for him were no doubt embarrassing when it came out, but he kept his job and reputation (mostly) intact because what's the point of punishing someone for making an honest mistake?

What these men did was incredibly heroic, and I would hope that I would do as they did if I was in their situation.  But. I don‚Äôt mean to be that guy, but I think it‚Äôs important for people to understand.  _Someone_ in charge still bent their morals horribly, for the _possibility_ of looking better- over the lives of thousands of people. Or were incredibly dim, and I severely hope that someone was morally bankrupt, because the alternative is worse.  My reasoning is simple; as someone familiar enough with the job of welding, and knowing the quality of steel they would need for this job, and where that steel has to come from.  They could have procured the steel, the welders, and welded the repairs on in less than 48 hours.  It would just mean that everyone in Manhattan is going to know about your mistake, and judge you for it. And it would cost you more money.  The reality is they waited, just working at night in secret, and scared the staff at the Red Cross excruciatingly, over the alternative- Cutting your losses, hiring every good pipeline welder in the state, call all the good steel yards in the state, spending the money, and fixing the problem. Much, much faster. Someone made that choice. Someone took a calculate risk, and it payed off.  But my phrasing betrays me. I see what happened as a _risk_ by someone. But I _know_ I don‚Äôt have as much information as they did.   Still, I don‚Äôt know if I would do differently. I‚Äôm not trying to pass judgment on the actions that everyone made, just trying to show people that there was not just one choice they could have made. And that all choice is more immensely complex than we can even imagine. Peace.

I dunno if it's my ADHD or what. But as the son of an accomplished Civil Engineer and an engineer myself (non-structural),  I can't imagine a project of this scale passing through the entire design phase without thinking about wind force on all sides of the building. Sure, the faces of tall buildings are what is typically important as they will take the majority of wind force. But with an unprecedented design like this one, I would think any architectural design firm, not to mention the dozens of engineers involved, would test all possible stresses on the design. Especially one like this in the middle of a densely populated city. I am baffled how this problem slipped through without anyone knowing. It more likely was known, at least to some, but ignored, IMO. If not, this is an extreme case of negligence. Not out of simple carelessness, but out of hubris. What an embarrassing legacy for the lead architect here. Hopefully it remains just that and doesn't end up one of the worst preventable man-made disasters in US history. It may be "fixed", but, is it really?

When I was a student at Berkley in the early 80's, four of us did a study of the Oakland Colosseum Arena.  The original design had just vertical columns below the "X" bracing. It looked to us, as baby architecture students early in our structural studies, like a "soft story" (lower floor that is less stiff than the structure above it, which is an earthquake hazard).  We called the architect at Skidmore Owings & Merrill.  He said it wasn't a soft story.  In our presentation to the class we said it looked to us like a soft story but the architect said it wasn't.  In the '90's they did a rehab of the building and added big shear walls in the not soft story.  Apparently it was a soft story after all!

Has anyone done a fatigue analysis?  The Citicorp building design is not dissimilar to the design of ships.   When the Trans-Alaska Pipeline System loaded its first tanker in 1977.  Depending on specific designs, fatigue cracks started to appear within a few years.  Over time, more cracks appeared, some in critical areas.  In 1991, the USCG issued a requirement that tankers involved in the TAPS trade develop a critical areas inspection plan.  The plan required identification of critical areas, usually done using finite element analysis, annual inspections of the critical areas, development of approved repairs, and record keeping of cracks and repairs made.  Rules for the design and construction of tankers evolved from the cracks found in tankers in the TAPS trade.  As a side note, the TAPS trade is unique in that it is primarily from Valdez to the US West Coast (Long Beach, San Francisco Bay, and Puget Sound), large number of annual trips, and significant weather.  Steel subjected to cyclical loading, from say varying winds, can result in fatigue cracking.   High stress areas should be visually inspected.  If necessary, non-destructive testing should be included.

This video raises several questions: 1. Why was the transportation of long diagonal beams across NYC deemed logistically impossibile? This sort of task was apparently achieved eight years earlier when the John Hancock Center was constructed in 1969; the diagonal beams were transported to the Chicago construction site using a combination of methods. Initially, crawler cranes were used to erect the steel from the foundation level up to the second floor. Then, to elevate the steel further, four "S2" towers with stiff-leg derricks were employed, supporting the erection from the second floor to the roof. These derricks had a capacity of 50 tons at a 30-foot radius and a maximum radius of 120 feet. The hoist engines for these derricks were located within the towers, which were "jumped" every four floors, allowing for the construction to proceed efficiently. 2.  Why should a tuned structural damper be at the mercy of a power outage? Surely a battery backup system could be installed to tide them over? Besides, according to my source, the Citigroup Center in NYC does NOT have a tuned mass damper, instead it has a tuned system that uses a fluid to dampen vibrations and reduce sway - this requires a very modest amount of electrical power. 3.  Does the wind loading hazard increase or diminish with time? On the one hand predicted climate change will increase the severity of hurricanes in the years to come. On the other hand, as more and more extreemely tall buidlings are erected each decade, shouldn't these act as wind breaks that reduce the wind load on earlier structures?

Peter Parker is an ordinary high school student living with his Aunt May and Uncle Ben in the bustling metropolis of New York City, trying to navigate the chaotic mess that is teenage life‚Äîschool, homework, crushes, friendship drama, and the occasional existential dread that comes from realizing the world is huge and confusing. Despite being smart and curious, he often feels invisible among his peers, overshadowed by kids who are more popular, more athletic, or just seemingly better at life, leaving him to quietly dream about doing something meaningful, something heroic, something that could make a difference in a world that sometimes feels indifferent. Then, during a seemingly normal school trip to a science exhibition, Peter‚Äôs life takes an unimaginable turn when he is bitten by a genetically modified spider, an event that seems small at first but changes everything forever. This bite grants him superhuman strength, the ability to leap incredible distances, stick to walls as though gravity no longer applies to him, and a mysterious and intuitive 'spider-sense' that tingles whenever danger is near, alerting him to threats in a way no normal human could comprehend. At first, Peter is exhilarated. He swings from streetlights, climbs walls effortlessly, and performs stunts that make him feel alive in ways he never imagined possible. He experiments with his newfound powers, entering wrestling matches for money, delighting in the cheers and recognition he had never received before. Life feels exciting, limitless, and powerful. But the exhilaration is short-lived. Tragedy strikes when his beloved Uncle Ben is killed by a criminal Peter could have stopped earlier, a painful lesson that forever changes his perspective. It is this loss, searing and personal, that teaches him the ultimate truth: "With great power comes great responsibility." Grieving, guilt-ridden, and morally awakened, Peter vows to dedicate his life to protecting the innocent and fighting injustice as Spider-Man, a hero in a city that is both vibrant and unforgiving. Soon, he faces his first real test in the form of the Green Goblin, Norman Osborn, a powerful businessman who, after experimenting on himself, becomes dangerously unstable and threatens the city with his twisted vision of control. Peter struggles to maintain balance‚Äîschoolwork, friendships, romantic feelings, and his own secret life as a masked hero‚Äîwhile facing escalating dangers. From battling petty criminals to dodging deadly weapons, from high-speed chases across the city‚Äôs skyline to tense confrontations that test his intelligence and moral compass, Peter is pushed to his limits. Each encounter teaches him new lessons about courage, sacrifice, and the complexity of heroism. The climactic battle with the Green Goblin is a test of everything Peter has learned: his agility, strength, ingenuity, and unwavering sense of responsibility. Using every tool at his disposal and thinking faster than ever before, he manages to defeat the Green Goblin, save countless lives, and protect the city he loves. By the end, Peter Parker has fully embraced his identity as Spider-Man. He understands that being a hero is not about recognition, fame, or glory‚Äîit is about selflessness, perseverance, and the ongoing responsibility to stand up for others, no matter the cost. The movie weaves thrilling action sequences, clever humor, heart-wrenching drama, and deeply human moments to tell a complete story of growth, resilience, and the transformation of an ordinary teenager into the legendary hero Spider-Man, illustrating that courage, responsibility, and compassion are the true powers that define a hero. It is, without a doubt, an epic, sprawling adventure that captures every single nuance of Peter Parker‚Äôs journey, from his earliest moments of doubt to his triumphant emergence as the city‚Äôs protector, and reading this summary is basically like living the movie scene by scene, swinging between buildings, feeling every fear, every triumph, every lesson, and every heartbeat of Spider-Man‚Äôs incredible story, and honestly, if you haven‚Äôt experienced it in this amount of detail, have you even fully understood the life-altering, wall-crawling, web-slinging saga that is the Spider-Man movie?

When Linkin Park first performed with Emily, I thought, no, this isn't right. She's awful‚Äîher past and her connection to Scientology, that's everything Chester stood against. I hated her, and I bad-mouthed her everywhere I could. I never listened to The Emptiness Machine. I just wanted Chester... We all love him, but sadly, he chose to end his life, leaving many people heartbroken. And yet, we will never forget him and never stop loving him. Recently, I thought about Mike's words... It will be hard, but whoever walks this path with us is warmly welcome. As I said, I resisted until the very end and hated Emily. But eventually, I thought, just listen to the new song anyway... And I have to say, it's really good. She's doing a great job. It's not the same LP as it used to be, it's something new, but with the energy of the old Chester. And Emily is getting better with every performance. You have to understand, she‚Äôs stepping into shoes she could never fill, and she knows that, but she doesn't have to. Chester is Chester, and Emily is Emily. And Linkin Park looks happier than they have in a long time. Chester will always be with them at every performance, and Chester wouldn‚Äôt want people to hate Emily the way I did back then. Give the girl a chance. As a hardcore LP fan, I resisted with every fiber of my being, but everyone deserves a chance, even Emily. She doesn‚Äôt sing the old songs perfectly‚Äîso what? There are better singers who could do it‚Äîso what? Not everyone has to like it, but this is how it is now, and we have to accept it. And to all the people who hate Emily because of Chester‚Äîlet go, let him rest in peace. Be glad that someone has the dignity and courage to step on stage and show: Guys, I‚Äôm doing this for you, for us, for everyone, and especially for Chester. I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs as bad as I thought a few weeks ago. She has a long way ahead of her, and she‚Äôll get better. One day, she‚Äôll become something like the female version of Chester. Just give her a chance. She‚Äôs not to blame for Chester leaving, and now she has to sing his songs. And her past is in the past, just like Chester‚Äôs. And still, Chester would say, love your neighbor, and give Emily love‚Äîhe would want nothing else. And again, I used to hate her too, but I think it's because we love Chester so much that we believe his legacy is being tarnished or forgotten through her. But that‚Äôs not the case. Chester always preached that love is the strongest force, and now, those same fans who accepted that are spreading hate? By doing so, you‚Äôre dishonoring his legacy, just as I did not too long ago. Let Chester go, and welcome Emily, as I did. And it wasn‚Äôt easy... really not easy.

When I first started listening to Linkin Park, I wanted to research the history of the band's name, and it turned out that they chose to be originally called "Lincoln Park" because every major city across America has a park or public place named after the 16th president, Abraham Lincoln. Their thought process was that the audience would think Lincoln Park is a local band, and that's how they would market themselves while performing live and starting out in the mid 90s. Now, with a new female lead singer, it pays homage to be thought of being as a local band, because Emily Armstrong wasn't really famous at all, probably a different style of rock music than Linkin Park itself, and probably wouldn't ever have imagined becoming a member of a male rock band, but I think that's why the remaining band members chose her to be their new voice, along with Mike Shinoda, such that there aren't super high expectations from her that she will be replacing Chester Bennington, which she absolutely can never do! But as artists, Linkin Park is constantly evolving and changing their styles, so even though Emily cannot immitate Chester, she can be that "local girl" who is the new voice of a band that originally called themselves "Lincoln Park"   R.I.P.
